title: UNSW Finsoc Presents: HSBC Women in Finance Mentoring Program
description:
The HSBC Women in Finance mentoring program is an annual mentoring program, supported by a range of sponsors in order to build meaningful relationships between motivated female finance students with successful finance industry professionals. 

Participating firms are from a range of finance and management consulting fields, including: HSBC, Bain & Company, Challenger, Citi, CFM, EY, Franklin Templeton Investments Australia, Lazard, Palisade Investment Partners, Shadforth, Westpac and more!

The program aims to bring together like minded students and professionals, creating opportunities to receive guidance from experienced and accomplished professions, in order to provide advice and to navigate a successful career in the finance industry.

Who are we looking for?
We are looking for female identifying UNSW finance students who are ambitious, motivated and driven, currently in their undergraduate or postgraduate degree.

What does being a mentee involve?
As a mentee, you will be required to attend several compulsory networking and professional events:
- Training day (11 April)
- HSBC Closing Event (24th of September)
In the opening event, you will meet your designated mentor. Both mentor and mentee will then arrange future meeting times, frequency or contact and method of correspondence. You will also be placed in a group of 4 with another pair of mentor-mentee. Both mentor and mentee are strongly encouraged to meet as a group of 2, 3 or 4 with the other mentor-mentee in order to further foster rapport and expand the network!

title: Allegro Private Equity Virtual Case Competition
description:
Are you familiar with the Private Equity industry, but don’t really know much about how the industry works and what they do? Have you ever wondered how Private Equity firms drive real organisational change and turn a company from bust to boom? 

Well if so, UNSW AISOC and UNIT USYD will be running our annual Private Equity case competition this year in collaboration with Allegro Funds. This year, we have a CASH PRIZE of $1,000 sponsored by Allegro Funds up for grabs for the winning team!

Allegro Funds have one of the largest Private Equity teams and have an amazing track record of creating value in a business regardless of how the business may be performing. They are Australia’s most-awarded team in the turnaround investing space!

-------- COMPETITION STRUCTURE --------

To compete, you will have to form a team of 3-4 people (must all be from the same university) with a minimum of ONE pre-penultimate student and choose a Team Leader to register your team through the link below. Private Equity is an area that embraces a diverse range of skills and experiences and therefore, diverse teams are encouraged and will be looked upon favourably. 

For those who have registered, a case brief will be sent via email on a set date and will require you to send in a slide deck of your solution to the case by the due date. Teams will present their case live via a web streaming platform to Allegro Funds representatives.

-------- WORKSHOP EVENT DETAILS -------- 

To assist in your preparation for this competition, in collaboration with Allegro Funds, we will be hosting an online virtual workshop on Tuesday 31st March at 6pm. title: Policy Submission for Climate Bill 2020
description:
The Policy Submissions Team is currently recruiting contributors for the submission to the Senate Environment and Communications Legislation Committee on the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Amendment (Climate Trigger) Bill 2020 and we are in turn inviting UNSW Law students to contribute to the submission. We strongly encourage everyone who is interested in this inquiry to apply to join the team who will be writing this submission as a contributor. The team will be led by our Policy Submissions Directors, Sarah Lu and Isobel Patmore.

We particularly encourage first year students to apply to gain an experience into what policy submissions are and to develop new skills and experiences. This inquiry is particularly well suited for students new to policy submissions. Keep in mind that this submission involves reading and commenting on proposed legislation.

This submission is about the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Amendment (Climate Trigger) Bill 2020. This legislation proposes amending the Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999, to introduce penalties for an individual or corporate body undertaking actions which involve mining operations, drilling exploration, land clearing or as specified in the regulations (emissions-intensive actions), if the action has, will have or is likely to have a significant impact on the environment.

======== DATA COMPETITION THEME ========
 
Teams will be provided datasets related to COVID-19, including the statistics over time (e.g. number of cases, recoveries etc.). Accompany optional datasets include financial and economic datasets, such as the fluctuating prices of gold, oil and Chinese Yuan before and during the outbreak. Teams are encouraged to find and use other datasets that may complement well to communicate the devastating financial impacts of COVID-19.

title: Inter-Varsity Tech Literacy Series | Capital W, NOW, WiB, WEB
description:
Introducing the Inter-Varsity Tech Literacy Series: organised by University of New South Wales' (UNSW) Capital W, Macquarie University’s Women Entering Business (WEB); the University of Sydney’s Network of Women (NOW); and the University of Technology Sydney’s Women in Business (WIB)

_____________________________________________________________

This series aims to empower female students in Business with skills in technology that translate to all fields of business so that they are better prepared to initiate their careers within an industry that continuously experiences disruptive innovation. 

The program will be presented as a series of four workshops and a Grand Challenge throughout 2020, each hosted by a different university and in collaboration with our potential sponsor companies Women in AI, DXC Tech, Google, Gradient Institute, IAG, IBM, Microsoft, Salesforce and Yellowfin:

- Workshop 1: Technology Tools (hosted by Capital W) [revised dates 27th, 28th March]
- Workshop 2: Technology Tools - Emerging (hosted by WEB) [21st, 22nd May]
- Workshop 3: Technology Fluency (hosted by NOW) [3rd July]
- Workshop 4: Future of Responsible Technology (hosted by WIB) [4th September]
- Grand Challenge: Competition focused on a mixture of themes [October/November]

PRIZES:
At the conclusion of the Grand Challenge, the winning team will have the opportunity to intern at one of the following companies: Microsoft, Salesforce, IAG, IBM and DXC Technology (the companies mentioned may be subject to change). The winning individual will have the opportunity to travel to Paris and visit the WAi headquarters in Paris - paid return airfare (economy) and accommodation (for days related to visiting WAi headquarters) included.

For more information on the workshops, please view: https://drive.google.com/open?id=1-bsKu0JTl4tgvsPlkZyX6ayYcljyDs62

We have deliberately targeted female students in Business in order to reduce gender bias and motivate talented female students with the skills and networks to become future leaders in the increasingly integrated business and technology space.
